03669nam a22004575i 9780773567320DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t19981998xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735673207 a10.1515/97807735673202doi  a(DE-B1597)656399  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBJ1533.G4bG6213 1998eb 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a306.41 aGodbout, Jacques T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWorld of the Gift /cAlain C. Caille, Jacques T. Godbout. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1998] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (259 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Does the Gift (Still) Exist? -- tThe Sites of the Gift -- tThree Forms of Social Bonding -- tInterpersonal Ties -- tWhen the State Supplants the Gift -- tThe Gift Between Strangers -- tThe Gift and Merchandise -- tThe Gift in Liberal Society -- tFrom the Archaic to the Modern Gift -- tThe Archaic Gift: Some Lessons in Ethnology -- tClassic Interpretations of the Archaic Gift -- tThe Archaic Gift and the Modern Gift -- tThe Passage to the Modern Gift -- tThe Strange Loop of the Gift -- tGift, Market, Disinterestedness -- tSketch for a Model of the Gift Relationship -- tConclusion: Behind Exchanges, the Gift -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe anthropologist Marcel Mauss, in his famous exploration of the gift in "primitive" and archaic societies, showed that the essential aspect of the exchange of presents involved the establishment of a social tie that bound the parties together above and beyond any material value of the objects exchanged. He argued that these intangible mutual "debts" constituted the social fabric. Godbout and Caillé show that, contrary to the modern assumption that societies function on the basis of market exchange and the pursuit of self-interest, the gift still constitutes the foundation of our social fabric. The authors describe the gift not as an object but as a social connection, perhaps the most important social connection because it creates a sense of obligation to respond in kind. They examine the gift in a broad range of cases such as blood and organ donation; volunteer work; the bonds between friends, couples, and family; Santa Claus; the interaction between performers and their audience; and the relation of the artist to society. Written in an engaging manner, The World of the Gift will appeal to anyone who is interested in how the world really operates.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aCaille, Alain C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356732040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773567320423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773567320/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles